BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Pen America": "https://pen.org/event/issues-in-our-stories/"}
X-SOURCE-ID:pen_america
SUMMARY:Finding the Issues in Our Stories and the Stories in Our Issues: A
  Member Exclusive Webinar
DTSTART;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260319T180000
DTEND;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260319T180000
UID:9aa0984169a0a2500ad596efcee54030@pen.org
DESCRIPTION:The current fraught socio-political climate is motivating writ
 ers to engage with social issues on the page. The personal is political\, 
 and the political is personal. In truth\, the writer has long played a rol
 e as a witness\, conscience\, and predictor of social change. How do we wr
 ite compellingly yet responsibly about social issues? By grappling with th
 e social issues at the core of our stories and by harnessing the narrative
  elements of stories embedded in the social issues we care about.\nWe are 
 thrilled to host\nKavita Das\n\, author of\nCraft and Conscience: How to W
 rite About Social\nIssues\n\, for a member-exclusive webinar about the rel
 ationship between the writer\, reader\, and subject\, and how writers can 
 think about applying the notions of context and narrative to their work. P
 articipants will have the opportunity to engage in writing exercises that 
 allow them to apply lessons on how they might balance doing justice to the
  issues they care about while telling a good story.\nThis is a member-excl
 usive event. If you are a member\, please visit the\nmember benefits\npage
  to access the registration link. Not a PEN America member?\nJoin today!\n
 Kavita Das\nis currently a Masters in Fine Arts candidate in creative nonf
 iction and screenwriting at Antioch University where she is the Eloise Kle
 in Healy Scholar. Kavita writes about culture\, race\, gender\, and their 
 intersections. Nominated for a Pushcart Prize\, her work has been publishe
 d in WIRED\, CNN\, Teen Vogue\, Catapult\, Fast Company\, Tin House\, Long
 reads\, The Atlantic\, The Washington Post\, Los Angeles Review of Books\,
  Kenyon Review\, NBC News Asian America\, Guernica\, Electric Literature\,
  Colorlines\, The Rumpus\, and elsewhere. Kavita’s second book Craft and
  Conscience: How to Write About Social Issues (Beacon Press\, October 2022
 ) is inspired by the Writing About Social Issues class she created and tea
 ches. Her first book\, Poignant Song: The Life and Music of Lakshmi Shanka
 r\, was published by Harper Collins India in 2019. Kavita liv
LOCATION:Online
URL:https://pen.org/event/issues-in-our-stories/
X-SOURCE:PEN America
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Pen America": "https://pen.org/event/the-ocean-our-liquid-universe/"}
X-SOURCE-ID:pen_america
SUMMARY:The Ocean: Our Liquid Universe
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260319T193000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260319T193000
UID:da2f8119c25d4498677652dcb7343ca8@pen.org
DESCRIPTION:Cost: 50-300\nDid you know that the Beatles’ “Octopus’s 
 Garden” predated the discovery of four underwater habitats where 6\,000 
 pregnant female octopuses gather in geothermal waters before giving birth?
 \nSet sail with PEN America and WORDTheatre for a one-night-only theatrica
 l event celebrating our blue planet.\nThe Ocean: Our Liquid Universe\n\, w
 hich audiences of all ages into the childlike awe and wonder the sea has i
 nspired for centuries—an exhilarating fusion of music\, stories\, poetry
 \, myth\, and scientific discovery\, brought vividly to life by an all-sta
 r cast of actors\, singers\, and musicians.\nExperience selections from li
 terature such as\nThe Odyssey\nand\nThe Old Man and The Sea\nalongside mus
 ic from Radiohead’s Thom Yorke and The Beatles.\nLearn more\nProfessiona
 l members of PEN America can avail 15% off all non-VIP tickets. If you are
  a member\, please visit the member\nbenefits page\nto access the discount
  code. Not a PEN America member?\nJoin today!
LOCATION:LA
URL:https://pen.org/event/the-ocean-our-liquid-universe/
X-SOURCE:PEN America
END:VEVENT
